post_text:
At last night’s Board of Education Special Session, the Laurel School Board approved the recommendation by Laurel’s Return to School Committee to modify the student start date of the 2020-2021 school year to Monday, September 14, 2020.

More GENERAL information will be shared in the coming days regarding what the beginning of Laurel’s school year will look like, including, but not limited to:

• Recommended hybrid schedules, which is a mix of in-person and remote learning
• Recommended start times and end times of the in-person student day for our elementary and secondary schools
• Remote-only learning options

More DETAILED information will be shared in the coming weeks regarding specific information and protocol for each of Laurel’s four schools as Laurel’s Return to School Committee completes its work on how to most safely reopen our schools.

Shawn Larrimore, Ed.D.
Superintendent

It doesn’t matter your socioeconomic status at all; our friends at the Laurel Ministerial Association and Mountaire want you to have a feast tonight.

So come on out at get a Free Food Box right now at LMHS.

We’ll see you soon.

post_text:
INSTANT ALERT

Hello Laurel Families, this is Dr. Larrimore with a very important announcement. Today, Governor Carney announced that students would not be returning to school on May 18 as originally hoped. Due to the continuing COVID-19 health crisis, school buildings will remain closed through the end of this school year.

However, students will continue to engage in remote learning plans that were established by the district. The remote learning plan will be in place through June 4th for seniors and through June 19th for all other students.

More information will be forthcoming next week regarding 3rd and 4th quarter grades and Commencement.

Our Grab n Go food program schedule will continue to operate on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays of each week.

We will also continue to work on finalizing our plans to finish out the school year and we will communicate these plans in a timely manner.

Please Stay Safe, Socially Distance Yourselves, And Flatten the Curve.

Hello Laurel Families, this is Dr. Larrimore with a very important message.

As our school district makes plans for moving from our HELP portal toward teacher-led remote learning, we desperately need your help in determining which of our families has access to the internet and viable technology and those who do not. I am asking that ALL parents please participate in a very brief Internet and Technology Survey so that we can better prepare for servicing all of our families. The survey will be by phone and will be sent out only one time. The Internet and Technology Survey will be sent out on Saturday, March 28, at 7:00 PM, and will be presented in English and in Spanish (A very Special Thanks to NLELA Staff Member, Andrea Henry for providing translation).

In advance, I appreciate your participation.

INSTANT ALERT

Good Morning Laurel Families, this is Dr. Larrimore with a highly important message for parents of LMHS students.

Earlier this morning, a smoke-like smell seemed to be emanating from the LMS side of the building. All LMS students were placed in the gymnasium until we could locate the source of the smell.

As of this alert, the source of the smell has not been located and nothing other than a strong smell has been detected.

However, for precautionary measures, The Laurel School District has decided to close LMHS for the remainder of the day and evening. At this point, all bus contractors have been alerted and all buses are returning to LMHS.

We will begin dismissal at 9:45 am for both Laurel Middle and Laurel High School. If your son or daughter is a rider, you may pick them up at 9:45 am.

Thank you for your cooperation in this matter as we want to err on the side of student and staff safety.

NLELA and LES are not affected and will be continuing with their normal student day.

Hello Laurel Families, this is Dr. Larrimore with a message regarding tomorrow, Friday, December 20.

Tomorrow, will be a JEANS and SPECIAL WEAR TOP Day for ALL Students and Staff.

Special Wear Tops include Spirit Wear, Ugly Sweaters, and general Holiday Tops.

Students are reminded that holes in jeans are not acceptable. Also, hoodies are not permitted.

And to clarify, appropriate jeans with a uniform top is also permitted, and also Uniform bottoms with a Special wear top is also permitted.

Students who choose not to participate in our Jeans/Special Wear Top Day MUST be in school uniform.

If your student DOES choose to take advantage of this jeans/special wear top day, please help us ensure that all students’ clothing choices are appropriate and modest.

Thank you and please have a happy and restful Winter Break.

First and foremost a tremendous thank you to our custodial team, grounds crew, technology department, Laurel administrators and educators, class/SGA advisors, athletics department, band, cheerleading squad, and many, many others who make this day so special for so many. However, a Special Thank you goes out to Lori Lewis, Susan Whaley, and Jami Gordy for their tireless work in making Homecoming Saturday better and better each year. It couldn't happen without them.

Congratulations to Homecoming Queen Alayzia Johnson and Homecoming King Bricen Sanders! And congratulations as well to Coach Joey Jones, the football staff and team for its exhilarating 27-21 overtime victory over Indian River! And a final Special Thanks to LHS Admin David Hudson and Rhiannon O'Neal and to our Laurel Board of Education, and our fine Laurel Community for their continued support. Can't wait for Homecoming Saturday 2020!

post_text: Amazing presentation at last night's Board meeting by rising freshmen Brayden Hearn and Aidan Bell. This summer, under the tutelage of LMS FFA advisor Sarah Ruggerio, the two future farmers received 1st Place in the state in their division at the AgriScience Fair. They now move on to the Big E (Big Eastern) Fair in Massachusetts in a few weeks for the regionals, and will then be off to Indiana in October to compete in the National AgriScience Fair! The duo's presentation researched the benefits that applying Humic Acid may have on plant yield in an effort to increase the world's food supply and curb world hunger!

Thank you.

post_text:
SAVA NAMED THE LAUREL SCHOOL DISTRICT TEACHER OF THE YEAR 2020
Donna Sava of Laurel Elementary School has been selected as The Laurel School District's Teacher of the Year for 2019-2020.

The announcement was made at the district's annual Teacher of the Year celebration on May 7 at Laurel Middle High School auditorium. Mrs. Sava was chosen as the district's overall winner.

Mrs. Sava has been a First Grade Teacher in The Laurel School District for 19 years. She holds a Bachelor's Degree from Radford Univeristy, Limited Certification in Special Education from Wilmington College, Master's Degree in Early Education from Wilmington College and completed additional Technology Courses through Delaware Tech Community College.

Teacher of the Year winners from each school building are as follows:

Kristen Pianka, North Laurel Early Learning Academy
Donna Sava, Laurel Elementary School
Sarah Ruggiero, Laurel Middle School

As the district's Teacher of the Year, Mrs. Sava is now eligible for the state Teacher of the Year Award, which will be announced in October.

CONGRATULATIONS MRS. SAVA!

INSTANT ALERT

Hello Laurel Families, this is Dr. Larrimore with an important message.

Although the state highway department and other first responders have done an amazing job cleaning up after this morning’s tornado, I still have many concerns about returning to school tomorrow.

The area on Alternate 13, from Discount Land Road to Duck-In Deli, including east of that on Camp Road, is closed and will likely stay closed through tomorrow afternoon, making transportation for these students an impossibility. Additionally, many homes are still without electricity. Finally, I have concerns that continued winds tomorrow could blow storm debris back onto the roads, creating hazardous driving conditions for our bus contractors, our parents, and our young student drivers.

For these reasons, The Laurel School District will be closed tomorrow, Tuesday, April 16. All practices, games, and extracurricular activities are cancelled as well.

Please stay safe.

post_text:
Hello Laurel Families, this is Dr. Larrimore with an important announcement.

Please join us on Monday, January 28, 2019 at 6:30 pm at Laurel Middle High School for our PROGRAMS NIGHT—a night in which we explain and explore all of our federal programs.
We will begin in the auditorium for an overview of our Title I, Perkins, and IDEA funding and the resources they provide our students, followed by breakout sessions.
Our Perkins Pathway sessions are:
Academy of Finance, Biomedical, Culinary, Plant Science, and Teacher’s Academy.
Title III Programs will be presented in the cafeteria beginning @ 6:30 pm.
Additionally, we invite parents of students served by our Special Education Department to attend sessions such as: “Understanding Parental Safeguards” and “What it means to have an IEP.”
We look forward to you joining us this Monday, January 28, to learn more about the opportunities provided to our students in the Laurel School District through our federal programs!
Laurel High School
